english:
  title: Lament on the New Calendar
  author: Eo Mu-jeok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I wish for thirty-six thousand days
    Divided into the seasons of human life—
    Spring flowers blooming red once every thousand years,
    Autumn moons shining white once every thousand years.
    Yao and Shun keep their youthful faces even now,
    Confucius and the Duke of Zhou still have jet-black hair.
    In the morning, sighs echo from the stone steps,
    In the evening, the sound of chanting drifts from the scholar's grove.
    The Yellow River runs clear twice in a year,
    The peaches of immortality ripen again every three years.
    With copper-handled chopsticks for Mount Tai's feast,
    With ladles and cups from the vast sea's bounty,
    I would sleep drunk alongside all the people,
    Singing together, "Ah, ah!" the song of the peaceful roads.
    Yet I would persuade the Jade Emperor to command the Grand Historian:
    Let the calendar be reformed but once in ten thousand ages.
  footnotes:
    - The thirty-six thousand days represents a complete cosmic cycle or ideal epoch.
    - Yao and Shun were legendary sage-kings of ancient China; the Duke of Zhou was Confucius's revered ancestor.
    - The stone steps and scholar's grove reference Confucian learning and virtue.
    - Mount Tai symbolizes abundance and cosmic significance in Chinese tradition.
    - The 'song of the peaceful roads' (康衢曲) references an ancient song expressing harmony and contentment among the people.
    - The 'Jade Emperor' and 'Grand Historian' represent celestial and earthly authority over time itself.
